{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486835"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:46:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:46:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"185"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/185"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.45,0.23,0.19,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"185"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90279"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/185"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"185"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74532"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1179"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1045"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30951"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38760"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90279"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 83-year-old woman attends the Emergency Department with a 24 hour history of increasing colicky abdominal pain and distension. Apart from a recent chest infection, she had been well up until this episode of pain, which has now become constant in nature. Her medical history includes a colectomy for carcinoma ten years earlier and she takes perindopril for hypertension. She is on warfarin for atrial fibrillation and was recently given a course of antibiotics for her chest infection. Two photographs of her abdomen are shown. The midline swelling is tender and soft to palpation (Image 1). The swelling is still visible when she lifts her shoulders off the bed (Image 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute diverticulitis","Incarcerated incisional hernia","Rectus sheath haematoma","Paraumbilical hernia","Large bowel obstruction"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA midline scar is clearly visible. Whilst the patient\u0027s abdomen is clearly distended, there are two irregular swellings, one on each of the scar. The swelling on the right side is still visible when she is asked to tense her rectus abdominis muscles (lifting her shoulder off the bed). This indicates that the swelling must either be arising in the subcutaneous tissues or protruding through the anterior abdominal wall. Given the options, the swelling is most likely to be a hernia. With the swelling being so close to the mid-line scar, the diagnosis is almost certainly going to be an \u003Cstrong\u003Eincarcerated incisional hernia\u003C/strong\u003E - and the patient\u0027s symptoms are suggestive of intestinal obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute diverticulitis\u003C/strong\u003E would be associated with constant abdominal pain - and usually situated in the left iliac fossa. A visible abdominal swelling would not be part of such a diagnosis. If the patient has intestinal obstruction secondary to the hernia, it will almost certainly be a small bowel obstruction. \u003Cstrong\u003ELarge bowel\u003C/strong\u003E getting obstructed in a hernia defect is uncommon. The swelling is well to the left of the umbilicus, so the swelling is very unlikely to be a \u003Cstrong\u003Eparaumbilical hernia\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith any patient on anticoagulants who presents with acute abdominal pain, the potential diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaematoma\u003C/strong\u003E formation must always be considered - particularly if they have recently been on another medication which might have increased the action of the anticoagulant. In this case, such a diagnosis is unlikely as a rectus sheath haematoma is usually be confined within the sheath and would be less apparent as an irregular mass.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Abdominal wall hernias are one of the commonest causes of small bowel obstruction."],"references":["Walking S, Angenete E, Block M, et al. Retrospective review of risk factors for surgical wound dehiscence and incisional hernia. BMC Surgery 2017; 17:19."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74532"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"185"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17492"},{"type":"media","id":"17493"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17492"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8ce02960-0679-483d-b38b-aed36fdc7372.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8ce02960-0679-483d-b38b-aed36fdc7372.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"17493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17493"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d063c7cb-f056-499a-b08e-0d95f9087e6e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d063c7cb-f056-499a-b08e-0d95f9087e6e.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74532"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-13T15:53:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-